<dl id="un2024j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2024">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un2all.htm#un2024j"> (VI.D.7) 24(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dirk in a sark</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Bloody carpet rags (<i>Amer</i>., imported to Liverpool). A mutilated man. All of a sudden the burly coloured man drew a razor from his pocket and started for the light-weight with the remark that he&apos;d make bloody carpet rags of him.&mdash;<cite>Newsp. Cutting</cite>. It should be added that the razor is the American negro&apos;s favourite weapon, carried as a rule in a high boot&mdash;something after the manner of a <mark>Scotch dirk in a Scotch sark</mark>. <small> J. Reading Ware, <a name="JRWP" href="/udra/udex.htm#jrwp"><cite title="source">Passing English of the Victorian Era</cite></a> (1909), 35</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c16248g" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16248g">VI.C.16:248(g)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
